# Auto PR after commit

When the user asks to **commit**, **check in**, **push**, or otherwise land work on a branch:

1. Follow the git safety protocol in user rules (status, diff, log, HEREDOC commit message).
2. **After a successful commit**, unless the user explicitly says not to:
   - Push the branch: `git push -u origin HEAD`.
   - Check for an open PR: `gh pr list --head $(git branch --show-current)`.
   - If none exists, create one with `gh pr create` against `main` (or the repo’s default base branch):
     - Title: concise summary of the branch intent.
     - Body: Summary bullets + Test plan checklist (include `pnpm --filter pawbuck typecheck` when consumer-app changed).
   - If a PR already exists, push only; mention the existing PR URL in the reply.
3. Return the **PR URL** to the user when a PR is created or updated.

## Skip auto-PR only when the user says

- “commit only”, “no PR”, “don’t push”, or similar.
- Work is on `main`/`master` with no feature branch.

## Do not

- Force-push unless explicitly requested.
- Open duplicate PRs for the same branch.
- Amend/push without user request when prior commit was already pushed.
